            "avatar_url": "https://zulip-avatars.s3.amazonaws.com/13/973e5363d617a705d4ec13541831691e8d846390?x=x&version=4",
            "client": "website",
            "content": "<p>Apparently I was full of shit when I said I wouldn't post here.  </p>\n<p>For a very long time, I was one of those people who felt the need to share EVERYTHING with their partner. It helped me bounce ideas off of someone when I was considering giving advice, it helped me vent when I needed that, and it made us feel very close. After a time I realized that I was sharing things that others had expected me to keep quiet. Since that's very disrespectful, I started keeping more things to myself, and I rarely feel like I have lost anything.</p>\n<p>I recall talking to one of my partners at the time about how my other partner was very stressed due to emotionally supporting someone in a difficult situation. I wanted to process some of my emotions about that situation, but I didn't want to share the details. My partner expected a lot more detail than I was willing to give, and it made me very angry. I think there is a large difference between, \"X is stressed because they're trying to help their friend out of a difficult situation\" and, \"X is stressed because Y [details about this stranger's living situation] [details about this stranger's health] [details about this stranger's work situation].\" I'm sure there are situations where sharing the former with a partner would not be acceptable, but there aren't many. To compare, sharing the latter seems like voyeurism.</p>\n<p>Currently, I don't tell any of my partners or friends everything, partially because a lot of those details are boring (\"And then I spent 2 hours on a layout bug\"), and partially because I don't feel like I owe anyone that. Sharing slightly less has not made any of my relationships less fulfilling.</p>",
