        {
            "avatar_url": "https://zulip-avatars.s3.amazonaws.com/13/5d6a7a4735c43e9dae0e3f9ef82919706728452a?x=x&version=3",
            "client": "website",
            "content": "<p>I think that this super depends on what you work environment is like, what your relationships are like, and a bunch of other things, but some general thoughts:</p>\n<ul>\n<li>You don't have to be out to everyone - you can be out to coworkers you're close to but not talk about relationship things with most people</li>\n<li>You can not mention people's names, and just say \"my partner\" for everyone (or \"my friend\" for everyone, if you prefer). If people are paying a lot of attention, they might realize that things don't line up, but when you're just making small talk, people mostly aren't paying attention and don't care about what you're saying \u00af\\_(\u30c4)_/\u00af This is the approach that I usually take for small talk, and I haven't had anyone really catch on who I hadn't already talked to about being poly.</li>\n</ul>\n<p>This can get more complicated when it comes to things like holiday parties, if that's something that your employer does, but I think generally it's helpful to remember when navigating this stuff that coworkers probably don't actually care that much about your life and are just making small talk out of habit (at least, in most of the environments that I've been in), so you really don't need to overthink it.</p>",
