        {
            "avatar_url": "https://zulip-avatars.s3.amazonaws.com/13/af4823dc0c1278b09771a37fca3a75a0562dcb3b?x=x&version=2",
            "client": "website",
            "content": "<p>One old approach to this is just not to talk about personal stuff at work. Or only talk about it if it comes up directly (\"Oh hey are you going to Pride?\" \"Yep.\").</p>\n<p>In my  experience--biased heavily in favor of startups where everything is too on fire to have time to waste doing stupid office drama, so take it for what it is--nobody cares about \"slutty\" behavior unless it involves other coworkers, their partners/spouses, clients, or investors. Everybody should be too busy creating shareholder value (lol) to be wasting time on that stuff.</p>\n<p>At a previous gig we had one openly pagan person, one openlypoly person with multiple partners and families, several other orientations and arrangements, at least one labor agitator, one green anarchist, and so on--but I think there's a difference between being openly &lt;x&gt; and bringing it up out of context. Our personal lives were of far less interest during conversation than blown milestones, internal project maneuvering, and so forth.</p>\n<p>And yeah, agree with Wesley--just use \"partner\" and let them be puzzled if they think too hard on it.</p>\n<p>EDIT: </p>\n<p>There is a secondary question to consider here, which is what being out means <em>to you</em>. Everyone kinda has to find their own way in that. For some folks, that means acknowledging their status and moving on with life. For other folks, that means actively including their friends and partners to the degree to which they're comfortable. For still others, that may mean aggressively and flamboyantly flaunting or proselytizing their status.</p>\n<p><strong>There's no wrong way to be out</strong>, but knowing yourself enough to know what your style is probably would help greatly in approaching this sort of question and having confidence in your direction.</p>",
