        {
            "avatar_url": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/27de1e4796502970d91435bdb9f420aa?d=identicon&version=1",
            "client": "website",
            "content": "<p>Dear Doctor Zu, I could use your advice on a situation I feel stuck in.</p>\n<p>I'm in a close relationship with K. Our approach to relationships is similar, and could probably be described as solo polyamory/relationship anarchy - a non-hierarchical approach that lets relationships develop naturally and without a predefined image of what they are \"supposed to\" look like.</p>\n<p>Now, K lives in a 4-person household, together with C. I'm interested in getting to know C better, but K is scared of that thought. The two of them had a situation in the past where they were interested in the same person, had a rivalry-like thing, and in the end, both lost touch with that person and blamed each other. Sometimes they seem to get along quite well, and other times, not at all.</p>\n<p>K said that she's nervous about C and me getting closer/falling in love. Also, she made it very clear that she doesn't want C to know about that. It has happened several times that C and me were at an event together, or just spent time together, and K felt horrible after that - she says that she's afraid she'll have to get less involved with me to protect herself, if C and me would be closer. I don't want K to feel horrible, and I want some stability in my relationships. Because of that, so far, I've kept my distance to C.</p>\n<p>But still, this feels very unresolved and unstable. I feel like I have no good options: if I get closer to C, that could lead to a lot of drama. At the same time, because of K's wishes, I don't feel like I can tell C <em>why</em> I'm keeping my distance, which seems unfair to her, and weird for me. I'd <em>like</em> to get to know C better, and I think she does, as well.</p>\n<p>I'm not sure what importance I should place on making sure that potential partners get along well, how to balance respecting K's privacy but not lying through omission to C, or how I could support K in processing her jealousy. When I bring this up with her, she gets scared and sad (and says that she usually avoids thinking about this), so that hasn't been really fruitful so far. And I can sympathize with those fears so much! But for me, in the long term, it has always been better to expose myself to the things I'm afraid of.</p>",
