        {
            "avatar_url": "https://zulip-avatars.s3.amazonaws.com/13/95eb11b4d11f06cdb3001ff6e17d64de5f38bb28?x=x&version=12",
            "client": "website",
            "content": "<p>The not being able to provide closure to C is the most challenging part of this entire thing. =( I am so sorry, Sebastian.</p>\n<p>I have shared a vertex in ... three distinct V's I think? One non-hierarchical, and two \"hierarchical\". Every relationship I have been in has had some level of conflict between myself and the person I was directly dating, but the V in which my metamour and I had tension between us was the above-and-beyond the most stressful and painful scenario. My friend referred to it as a \"double-bind\" for the reason you are noticing. There is <em>no answer</em> that is going to result in minimal pain. Every party is going to be hurt on some level, no matter which decision you make. K has a lot of trauma from the past double-bind she has been part of for that reason. She is setting a boundary against being in another. As someone who also has trauma from my past double-bind, I deeply, deeply empathise with this. </p>\n<p>If I were in this situation, I think this is a conversation that I would encourage to happen between K and C, and that I would actually suggest having a polyamory-friendly couples therapist facilitating that conversation. But otherwise, you are stuck between a rock and a hard place. I think it is almost impossible for relationships to not have some form of affect on each other, and for commitments to not slowly occur over time, which is why I do not really identify as a relationship anarchist anymore.</p>\n<p>How you move forward in terms of deciding whether to honour K's boundaries and artificially restrict a nascent intimacy...is in your court. No one can really advise you on what to do there. Nobody else really knows about the nature of your commitment to K or the extent towards your feelings for C, or how much you relatively weigh the ethics of honouring existing relationship commitments vs allowing a third party to dictate the intimacy of a relationship they are not a part of. But I think for K's and C's sake, I hope they do approach this together, considering that they continue to be part of the same polyamorous community.</p>",
