        {
            "avatar_url": "https://secure.gravatar.com/avatar/22a26ea43a6ad80dc294adbc8d4406ac?d=identicon&version=1",
            "client": "website",
            "content": "<p>I actually made a note last night to do some journalling about this, so maybe I'll start by writing out some things here haha.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>I've been thinking about attachment styles more recently, partially because multiple friends of mine have read about it and been thinking about it, and also because these days I've been especially craving romantic attention and noticing that most of the people I have romantic feelings for are dismissive-avoidant-esque, and this is inconvenient :p Though I think it's pretty interesting that I've ended up in this situation.</p>\n<p>One thing that's worth mentioning right off the bat is that people definitely will fall into different categories of attachment in different relationships, or even different moments of the same relationship. I notice myself in more long-term situations where I will tend towards anxious-attached, and more short-term situations where I'm more dismissive (and then I'm so dismissive that I essentially kill the friendship/relationship ...and then I'm no longer actively in the dismissive role ^^')  I'm pretty sure this is why most of my surviving relationships have me in more of the anxious role? I guess I'm more comfortable in that role and more familiar with how to manage  those feelings? (More journalling to be done there, lol) </p>\n<p>And my friend was also telling me that even if you're usually securely attached, it can be easy to end up anxious around a very dismissive person or to end up dismissive around a very anxious person. So yeah, definitely seems more useful as ways to describe behaviour than ways to label people.</p>\n<hr>\n<p>why is it useful?</p>\n<p>Attachment style theory can be super useful for the same reason as a lot of other personality tests or labels or whatever - it's a way to better understand parts of yourself, through conversations about shared experience, and through learning about various research and therapy and advice around these common patterns.</p>\n<p>It seems pretty common that people end up in relationships where they're pretty deep into playing out the anxious/dismissive dynamic and get stuck, and find it hard to communicate their needs and especially hard to understand why the other person is acting so differently than them (and why they're acting that way). Attachment theory and the conversation around it gives you language you can use to communicate about it.</p>\n<p>Like, I love <a href=\"/user_uploads/13/uFRmQO9PTtgeL1p2oK9lUj-W/image.png\" title=\"image.png\">posts like this one</a> ( <a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/B-qlFKBh8b1/\" title=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/B-qlFKBh8b1/\">insta link</a>) that help me understand the ways someone might be feeling if they're acting dismissively. And <a href=\"/user_uploads/13/mq5IX3UrIJRZU2ff9g4tWs8Y/image.png\" title=\"image.png\">this post</a> (<a href=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/B-lFX3_BJDJ/\" title=\"https://www.instagram.com/p/B-lFX3_BJDJ/\">source</a>) gives me ideas for ways to communicate my needs when I'm feeling anxious. (It also helps me feel more validated for desiring these things! Like, wow, it's reasonable to just ask for that?) When people are feeling uncomfortable, it's often harder to communicate well, and attachment theory provides language that has been useful to a lot of people.</p>\n<div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/13/uFRmQO9PTtgeL1p2oK9lUj-W/image.png\" title=\"posts like this one\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/13/uFRmQO9PTtgeL1p2oK9lUj-W/image.png\"></a></div><div class=\"message_inline_image\"><a href=\"/user_uploads/13/mq5IX3UrIJRZU2ff9g4tWs8Y/image.png\" title=\"this post\"><img src=\"/user_uploads/13/mq5IX3UrIJRZU2ff9g4tWs8Y/image.png\"></a></div><p>For some people this is eye opening because they just didn't realize that they do this at all, that they have these needs, that their behaviour is interpreted in whatever way. In reading about attachment theory and discovering (or becoming more clearly aware of) a bunch of things about yourself or people close to you, a bunch of opportunities open up to make changes to help your relationships feel more healthy.</p>\n<p>For me it was really nice to just have words to describe it, both to explain to others how I feel, and also to be able to clearly reach the point of thinking \"ah yes, we're just both stressed about this relationship in our own ways, and that happens to easily feedback loop on itself making things more intensely uncomfortable, and now that I know that I can use commonly discussed strategies and language to help this relationship feel more stable\". I could have reached this point without attachment style theory (and in some ways, I did), but it feels way easier to think about this stuff within the context of lots of existing research and terminology.</p>",
